{"parse":{"title":"home","pageid":8991,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Home|homẽ|home-|Hô-me}}\n==English==\n{{wp|<dab>}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|en|hyem||Northumbrian}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*ḱey-|*tḱey-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|hōm}}, from {{inh|en|ang|hām}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*haim}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*haimaz|t=home, village}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*ḱóymos|t=village, home}}, from the root {{m|ine-pro|*tḱey-|}}. {{dbt|en|heyem}}.\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|sco|hame|t=home}}, {{cog|yol|haime}}, {{m|yol|hime}}, {{m|yol|hyme|t=home}}, {{cog|stq|Heem|t=home}}, {{cog|gsw|haim}}, {{m|gsw|hei}}, {{m|gsw|heim}}, {{m|gsw|hemmu|t=home}}, {{cog|bar|hama}}, {{m|bar|hame|t=home}}, {{cog|cim|hòam}}, {{m|cim|huam|t=home}}, {{cog|nl|heem}}, {{m|nl|heim|t=home}}, {{cog|de|Heim|t=home}}, {{cog|li|heim}}, {{m|li|Héïm|t=home}}, {{cog|lb|Heem|t=home}}, {{cog|mhn|hoa'm|t=home}}, {{cog|wym|ham}}, {{m|wym|hām}}, {{m|wym|haom|t=home}}, {{cog|yi|היים|t=home}}, {{cog|da|hjem|t=home}}, {{cog|fo|-}}, {{cog|is|heim|t=home}}, {{m|is|heimur|t=world}}, {{cog|nb|heim}}, {{m|nb|hjem|t=home}}, {{cog|nn|heim|t=home}}, {{cog|sv|hem|t=home}}, {{cog|got|𐌷𐌰𐌹𐌼𐍃|t=village}}, {{cog|ga|caoimh||dear}}, {{cog|lt|kaimas|t=village}}, {{m|lt|šeima||t=family}}, {{cog|sq|komb|t=nation, people}}, {{cog|grc|κώμη|t=village}}, from {{cog|ine-pro|*ḱey-|t=to lie}} (compare {{cog|hit|tr=kittari|t=it lies}}, {{cog|grc|κεῖμαι|t=to lie down}}, {{cog|la|civis|t=citizen}}, {{cog|ae|𐬯𐬀𐬉𐬙𐬈|t=he lies, rests}}, {{cog|sa|शये||tr=śáye|t=he lies}}).\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{enPR|hōm|a=RP}}, {{IPA|en|/həʊm/}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Pvanp7-home.wav|a=UK}}\n* {{enPR|hōm|a=US}}, {{IPA|en|/hoʊm/}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-home.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{IPA|en|[hoːm]|a=CA}}\n* {{IPA|en|/hom/|a=Scotland}}\n* {{homophones|en|Home|hom|holm|heaume|holme}}\n* {{rhymes|en|əʊm|s=1}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# ''A [[dwelling]].''\n## One’s own [[dwell]]ing place; the [[house]] or structure in which one [[live]]s; especially the house in which one lives with one's [[family]]; the habitual [[abode]] of one’s family.\n##* {{RQ:Tyndale NT|John|20|10|clj|And the diſciples went awaye agayne vnto their awne '''home'''.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1808|author=w:John Dryden|editor=w:Walter Scott|title=The Works of John Dryden\n|passage=Thither for ease and soft repose we come: / '''Home''' is the sacred refuge of our life; / Secured from all approaches, but a wife.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1822|author=w:John Howard Payne|title=w:Home! Sweet Home!\n|passage='''Home'''! '''home'''! sweet, sweet '''home'''! / There’s no place like '''home''', there’s no place like '''home'''.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1981|author=w:William Irwin Thompson|title=The Time Falling Bodies Take to Light: Mythology, Sexuality and the Origins of Culture|publisher=Rider/Hutchinson & Co.|location=London|page=132|passage=If we now say that \"woman's place is in the '''home''',\" it is not because men put her there, but because the '''home''' became the capitol of women's mysteries.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-29|volume=407|issue=8842|page=28|magazine=w:The Economist|title=[http://www.economist.com/news/asia/21580209-natural-disaster-aggravated-poor-response-high-and-wet High and wet]\n|passage=Rock-filled torrents smashed vehicles and '''homes''', burying victims under rubble and sludge.}}\n## The place (residence, settlement, country, etc.), where a person was [[born]] or [[raise]]d; [[childhood]] or [[parental]] home; home of one’s parents or [[guardian]].\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=2004|author=Jean Harrison|title='''Home'''\n|passage=The rights listed in the UNCRC cover all areas of children's lives such as their right to have a '''home''' and their right to be educated.}}\n##: {{ux|en|Does she still live at '''home'''? - No, she moved out and got an apartment when she was 18, but she still lives in the city.}}\n## The [[abiding]] place of the [[affection]]s, especially of the [[domestic]] affections.\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1821|author=w:George Gordon Byron|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/21700/21700-h/21700-h.htm|title=Don Juan|section=canto III\n|passage=He enter’d in the house—his '''home''' no more, / For without hearts there is no '''home''';{{...}}}}\n## A house that has been made home-like, to suit the comfort of those who live there.\n##: {{ux|en|It's what you bring into a house that makes it a '''home'''}}\n## A place of [[refuge]], [[rest]] or [[care]]; an [[asylum]].\n##: {{ux|en|a '''home''' for outcasts}}\n##: {{ux|en|a '''home''' for the blind}}\n##: {{ux|en|a veterans' '''home'''}}\n##: ''Instead of a [[pet store]], get your new dog from the local dogs’ '''home'''''.\n##: {{ux|en|Our grandmama's moved into a '''home'''.}}\n## {{lb|en|by extension}} The grave; the final rest; also, the native and eternal dwelling place of the soul.\n##* '''1769''', King James Bible, Oxford Standard text, [[s:Bible (King James)/Ecclesiastes|Ecclesiastes]] 12:5:\n##*: {{...}}because man goeth to his long '''home''', and the mourners go about the streets: {{...}}\n## {{lb|en|by extension}} Anything that serves the functions of a home, as comfort, safety, sense of belonging, etc.\n##* {{quote-journal|en|journal=Workers World|author=Leslie Feinberg|url=https://ia804705.us.archive.org/23/items/lavender-and-red/Lavender_and_Red.pdf#page=295|title=1976 WWP pamphlet found answers in Marxism|date=10 Jan 07|text=The rights of modern transsexual women and men to live in the sex that is \"'''home'''\".}}\n# One’s [[native]] land; the place or [[country]] in which one dwells; the place where one’s ancestors dwell or dwelt.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1863|author=w:Nathaniel Hawthorne|title=Our Old '''Home''': A Series of English Sketches|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/8090/pg8090.txt\n|passage=Visiting these famous localities, and a great many others, I hope that I do not compromise my American patriotism by acknowledging that I was often conscious of a fervent hereditary attachment to the native soil of our forefathers, and felt it to be our own Old '''Home'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1889|year_published=1899|author={{w|Rudyard Kipling}}|title={{w|Under the Deodars}}|chapter=The Hill of Illusion|location=Boston|publisher=The Greenock Press|page=93|text=Have you ''any'' people at '''Home''', Guy, to be pleased with your performances?}}\n#* {{RQ:Ferguson Zollenstein|IV\n|passage=So this was my future '''home''', I thought! Certainly it made a brave picture. I had seen similar ones fired-in on many a Heidelberg stein. Backed by towering hills,{{...}}a sky of palest Gobelin flecked with fat, fleecy little clouds, it in truth looked a dear little city; the city of one's dreams.}}\n#* '''1980''', {{w|Peter Allen}}, song, ''{{w|I Still Call Australia Home}}'':\n#*: I've been to cities that never close down / From New York to Rio and old London town / But no matter how far or how wide I roam / I still call Australia '''home'''.\n# The [[locality]] where a thing is usually found, or was first found, or where it is naturally abundant; [[habitat]]; [[seat]].\n#: {{ux|en|the '''home''' of the pine}}\n#* '''1706''', {{w|Matthew Prior}}, ''An Ode, Humbly Inscribed to the Queen, on the ẛucceẛs of Her Majeẛty's Arms, 1706'', as republished in '''1795''', Robert Anderson (editor), ''The Works of the British Poets'':\n#*: {{...}}Flandria, by plenty made the '''home''' of war, / Shall weep her crime, and bow to Charles r'estor'd,{{nb...}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1849|author=w:Alfred Tennyson|title=s:In Memoriam A. H. H.\n|passage=Her eyes are '''homes''' of silent prayer, / Nor other thought her mind admits / But, he was dead, and there he sits, / And he that brought him back is there.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-09-07|volume=408|issue=8852|magazine=w:The Economist|title=[http://www.economist.com/news/science-and-technology/21584965-two-nasty-childhood-illnesses-africa-are-coming-under-scientific Nodding acquaintance]\n|passage=Africa is '''home''' to so many premier-league diseases (such as AIDS, childhood diarrhoea, malaria and tuberculosis) that those in lower divisions are easily ignored.}}\n# ''A focus point.''\n## {{lb|en|board games}} The ultimate point aimed at in a progress; the [[goal]].\n##: {{ux|en|The object of Sorry! is to get all four of your pawns to your '''home'''.}}\n## {{lb|en|baseball}} [[home plate|Home plate]].\n## {{lb|en|lacrosse}} The place of a [[player]] in front of an opponent’s [[goal]]; also, the player.\n## {{lb|en|Internet}} The [[landing page]] of a website; the site's [[homepage]].\n## {{lb|en|music|informal}} The chord at which a melody starts and to which it can resolve.\n# {{lbl|en|computers}} {{clipping of|en|home directory}}.\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{sense|one’s own dwelling place}} {{l|en|tenement}}, {{l|en|house}}, {{l|en|dwelling}}, {{l|en|abode}}, {{l|en|domicile}}, {{l|en|residence}}\n* {{sense|(baseball) home plate}} {{l|en|home base}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col3|en|title=Terms derived from ''home'' (noun)|a house is not a home\n|a man's home is his castle\n|America at home\n|an Englishman's home is his castle\n|at home\n|at-home card\n|at-homeness\n|away from home\n|back home|tourist home\n|birthhome\n|boys' home\n|bring home\n|bring home the bacon\n|broken home\n|cage home\n|care home\n|charity begins at home\n|children's home\n|Chinese home run\n|close to home|he's-at-home|home field|home pitch\n|come home by weeping cross|home birth\n|come home to roost\n|cottage home\n|detention home\n|direct-to-home\n|dishome\n|don't try this at home\n|down-home\n|down home\n|dream home\n|drive home\n|eat someone out of house and home\n|eco-home\n|eventide home\n|fall home\n|family home evening\n|far-from-home\n|follow-home\n|forever home\n|foster home\n|from home\n|funeral home\n|furever home\n|ghost home\n|give someone a lift home\n|go big or go home\n|go hard or go home\n|group home\n|hammer home\n|harvest home\n|have