\n* German: {{tt+|de|Heim|n}}, {{tt+|de|Ruhestätte|f}}\n*: Bavarian: {{tt|bar|Ham}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|άσυλο|n}}\n* Karachay-Balkar: {{tt|krc|уя}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{tt+|ckb|ماڵ}}\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{tt+|kmr|mal}}\n* Latin: {{tt+|la|domus|f}}, {{tt+|la|aedes|f-p}}, {{tt+|la|tēctum|n}}, {{tt+|la|aedificium|n}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|прибежиште|n}}\n* Middle English: {{tt|enm|hom}}\n* Nahuatl: {{tt+|nah|chantli}}\n* Norwegian: {{tt+|no|hjem}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|lar|m}}\n* Scots: {{tt|sco|hame}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|dachaigh|f}}\n* Slovene: {{tt+|sl|dóm|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|asilo|m}}, {{t+|es|hogar|m}}, {{t+|es|techo|m}}\n* Tamil: {{t+|ta|உறையுள்}}, {{t+|ta|வசிப்பிடம்}}\n* Telugu: {{tt|te|శరణాలయము}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|yuva}}\n* Vietnamese: {{qualifier|home for outcasts, handicapped, elderly, etc.}} {{t+check|vi|viện|lit=institution}}, {{qualifier|home for orphans}} {{t-check|vi|trại mồ côi}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|goal (sports)}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|meta|f}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|domov|m}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|meta|f}}, {{tt+|it|traguardo|m}}\n* Scots: {{tt|sco|hame}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|meta|f}}, {{tt+|es|portería|f}}, {{tt+|es|puerta|f}}, {{t+|es|arco|m}} {{i|Latin America}}\n* Vietnamese: {{tt+|vi|đích}}\n* Yoruba: {{t|yo|ilé}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top-also|home directory|home directory}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|inici|m}}\n* Finnish: {{tt|fi|kotihakemisto}}, {{tt|fi|kotikansio}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt|hu|kezdőkönyvtár}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|inicio|m}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|hem|n}}, {{tt+|sv|hemkatalog|c}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Afrikaans: {{tt+check|af|tuiste}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt+check|eo|hejmo}}\n* Interlingua: {{tt+check|ia|casa}}\n* Old English: {{tt-check|ang|eard}} {{q|1|2|3|4|5}}, {{tt-check|ang|hām}} {{q|1}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+check|ro|casă|f}}\n* Rwanda-Rundi: {{tt-check|rw|urugo}}\n* Thai: {{tt+check|th|บ้าน|tr=bâan}}, {{tt+check|th|ที่อยู่|tr=tee-yoo}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+check|tr|ev}}, {{tt+check|tr|yurt}}\n* Welsh: {{tt+check|cy|tref|f}}\n* Woiwurrung: {{t-check|wyi|wilam}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n}}<!-- close {{multitrans}} -->\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|of|animals|intransitive}} To [[return]] to its owner.\n#: {{ux|en|The dog '''homed'''.}}\n\n====Related terms====\n{{col|en\n|home in\n|homing pigeon\n}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{multitrans|data=\n{{trans-top|to home (\"in on\")}}\n* Danish: {{tt|da|sigte|alt=sigte ind på}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|mikken}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|hakeutua}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|anpeilen}}, {{tt+|de|zielen}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|centrare}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|се наведува}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|наводи́ться|impf}}, {{tt+|ru|навести́сь|pf}}\n* Slovene: {{tt|sl|nameriti}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|sikta|alt=sikta in på}}\n* Telugu: {{tt+|te|ఇంటికి}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n}}<!-- close {{multitrans}} -->\n\n===Adjective===\n{{en-adj|-}}\n\n# Of, from, or pertaining to one’s [[dwelling]] or [[country]]; [[domestic]]; not [[foreign]]. {{defdate|from 13th c.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''home''' manufactures|'''home''' comforts}}\n# {{lb|en|now|rare|except in phrases}} That strikes home; [[direct]], [[pointed]]. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}\n#: {{ux|en|a [['''home''' truth]]}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[personal|Personal]], [[intimate]]. {{defdate|17th–19th c.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1778|author=w:Frances Burney|title=Journals & Letters|page=91|publisher=Penguin|year_published=2001\n|passage=I hardly knew what I answered him, but, by degrees I ''tranquillised'', as I found he forbore distressing me any further, by such '''''Home''''' strokes […].}}\n# {{lb|en|sports}} Relating to the [[home team]] (the team at whose venue a game is played). {{defdate|from 19th c.}}\n#: {{ant|en|away|road|visitor}}\n#: {{ux|en|the '''home''' end, '''home''' advantage, '''home''' supporters}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|title=Terms derived from ''home'' (adjective)\n|home base\n|home brew\n|Home Counties\n|home economics\n|home farm\n|home front\n|home ground\n|Home Guard\n|home lot\n|home market\n|home movie\n|home page\n|home port\n|home plate\n|home range\n|home remedy\n|home rule\n|home ruler\n|home run\n|home signal\n|home stretch\n|home theater\n|home thrust\n|home truth\n|home turf\n|home video\n|homeworking,home working\n}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top-see|adjective|residential}}\n* Spanish: {{t|es|hogareño}}, {{t+|es|casero}}, {{t+|es|domiciliario}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{en-adv|-}}\n\n# To one's [[#English|home]].\n## To one's place of [[residence]] or one's customary or official location.\n##: {{ux|en|[[go '''home''']]}}\n##: {{ux|en|come '''home'''}}\n##: {{ux|en|carry someone '''home'''}}\n##: {{ux|en|I invited them '''home'''.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1863|author=w:Nathaniel Hawthorne|title=Our Old Home: A Series of English Sketches|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/8090/pg8090.txt\n|passage=He made no complaint of his ill-fortune, but only repeated in a quiet voice, with a pathos of which he was himself evidently unconscious, \"I want to get '''home''' to Ninety-second Street, Philadelphia.\"}}\n##* {{RQ:Besant Ivory Gate|chapter=Prologue|page=16|passage=Athelstan Arundel walked '''home''' all the way, foaming and raging. No omnibus, cab, or conveyance ever built could contain a young man in such a rage. His mother lived at Pembridge Square, which is four good measured miles from Lincoln's Inn.}}\n## To one's [[place of birth]].\n## To the place where it [[belong]]s; to the end of a course; to the full length.\n##: {{ux|en|She drove the nail '''home'''}}\n##: {{ux|en|ram a cartridge '''home'''}}\n##* {{RQ:Shakespeare Othello|5|1|text=Wear thy good rapier bare, and put it '''home''': {{...}}}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1988|author=Roald Dahl|title=Matilda\n|passage=Eventually she managed to slide the lid of the pencil-box right '''home''' and the newt was hers. Then, on second thoughts, she opened the lid just the tiniest fraction so that the creature could breathe.}}\n## {{lb|en|internet}} To the [[home page]].\n##: {{ux|en|Click here to go '''home'''.}}\n# At or in one's place of [[residence]] or one's customary or official location; [[at home]].\n#* '''1975-1976''', [[w:Lou Sullivan|Lou Sullivan]], personal diary, quoted in '''2019''', Ellis Martin, Zach Ozma (editors), ''We Both Laughed In Pleasure''\n#*: I'm certainly not the type to sit '''home''' waiting up for hubbie every night.\n# To a full and intimate degree; to the heart of the matter; [[fully]], [[directly]].\n#* '''1625''', {{w|Francis Bacon}}, dedication to the Duke of Buckingham, in ''Essays Civil and Moral'',\n#*: I do now publish my Essays; which of all my other works have been most current : for that, as it seems, they come '''home''' to men's business and bosoms.\n#* {{RQ:South Twelve Sermons |text=How '''home''' the charge reaches us, has been made out by ẛhewing with what high impudence ẛome amongẛt us defend sin, {{...}}}}\n#* {{RQ:Richardson Clarissa|letter=67|text=Her treatment of you, you say, does no credit either to her education or fine sense. Very '''home''' put, truly!}}\n# {{lb|en|UK|soccer}} into the [[goal]]\n#* '''2004''', [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/3496755.stm Tottenham 4-4 Leicester], [[w:BBC Sport|BBC Sport]]: February,\n#*: Walker was penalised for a picking up a Gerry Taggart backpass and from the resulting free-kick, Keane fired '''home''' after Johnnie Jackson's initial effort was blocked.\n# {{lb|en|nautical}} into the right, proper or [[stowed]] position\n#: {{ux|en|sails sheeted '''home'''}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n* {{m|en||home}} is often used in the formation of compound words, many of which need no special definition; as, home-brewed, home-built, home-grown, etc.\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{sense|to home}} {{l|en|homeward}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|title=Terms derived from the adverb ''home''\n|be home\n|bring home|get home bag|take home\n|come home\n|drive home\n|get home\n|go home\n|haul home the sheets of a sail\n|out-and-home\n|return home\n|till the cows come home\n|turn home|going home club|loser back home\n}}\n\n====Related terms====\n{{col|en\n|homing\n|homeless\n|homely\n|homeowner\n|homestead\n|homey,homy\n|home away from home\n|home and dry\n|home and hosed\n|home free\n|parental home\n|hometown\n}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{multitrans|data=\n{{trans-top|at home}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt|be|до́ма}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt|bg|у дома}}\n* Catalan: {{tt|ca|a casa}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt|cmn|在家里|tr=zài jiālǐ}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|doma}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|hjemme}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|thuis}}\n* Elfdalian: {{tt|ovd|iema}}\n* Faroese: {{tt+|fo|heima}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kotona}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|à la maison}}, {{t+|fr|à domicile}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|daheim}}, {{tt+|de|zu Hause}}, {{tt+|de|zuhause}}\n*: Bavarian: {{tt|bar|dahoam}}\n* Greek: {{tt|el|[[στο]] [[σπίτι]]}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{tt|grc|οἴκοι}}\n* Hindi: {{tt|hi|घर पर}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|otthon}}, {{tt+|hu|itthon}}\n* Hunsrik: {{tt|hrx|dehemm}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|heima}}\n* Ido: {{tt+|io|heme}}, {{tt+|io|enheme}}\n* Irish: {{tt|ga|sa bhaile}}\n* Italian: {{tt|it|a casa}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|家|tr=うちに, uchi ni|alt=家に}}, {{tt+|ja|家|tr=うちで, uchi de|alt=家で}}\n* Korean: {{tt|ko|[[집]][[-에]]}}\n* Latin: {{tt+|la|domi}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t|lt|namie}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|дома}}\n* Navajo: {{tt|nv|hooghandi}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt+|no|hjemme}}, {{tt+|no|heime}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{tt+|nn|heime}}\n* Pennsylvania German: {{tt|pdc|deheem}}\n* Persian: {{tt+|fa|منزل|tr=manzel}}, {{tt|fa|در منزل|tr=dar manzel}}\n* Polish: {{tt|pl|[[w]] [[dom]]u}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt|pt|em casa}}\n* Romani: {{tt|rom|khere}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|acasă}}\n* Romansh: {{tt|rm|a chasa}} {{qualifier|Rumantsch Grischun|Vallader}}, {{tt|rm|a casa}} {{qualifier|Sursilvan}}, {{tt|rm|a tgea}}, {{tt|rm|a tgeasa}} {{qualifier|Sutsilvan}}, {{tt|rm|a tgesa}} {{qualifier|Surmiran}}, {{tt|rm|a chesa}} {{qualifier|Puter}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|до́ма}}\n* Sami:\n*: Northern Sami: {{tt|se|ruovttus}}\n* Scots: {{tt|sco|hame}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|dhachaigh}}\n* Sinhalese: {{tt+|si|ගෙදර}}\n* Slovak: {{tt+|sk|doma}}\n* Slovene: {{tt+|sl|domá}}\n* Sorbian:\n*: Lower Sorbian: {{tt|dsb|doma}}\n* Spanish: {{tt|es|en casa}}, {{t+|es|presente}} {{q|when the inquirer is at the door|adjective}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|hemma}}\n* Tamil: {{t|ta|[[வீடு|வீட்]][[இல்|டில்]]}}\n* Telugu: {{tt|te|ఇంటి వద్ద}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|evde}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt+|uk|вдо́ма}}\n* Urdu: {{tt|ur|گھر پر|tr=ghar par}}\n* Uyghur: {{tt|ug|ئۆيدە}}\n* Welsh: {{tt|cy|gartref}}, {{tt|cy|gartre}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|homewards}}\n* Armenian: {{tt+|hy|տուն}}\n* Asturian: {{tt|ast|a casa}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt|be|дадо́му}}\n* Bengali: {{t-needed|bn}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|d'ar gêr}}\n* Catalan: {{tt|ca|a casa}}\n* Cherokee: {{t-needed|chr}}\n* Chichewa: {{t-needed|ny}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|在家|tr=zài jiā}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|domů}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|hjem}}, {{tt|da|hjemad}}\n* Dhivehi: {{t-needed|dv}}\n* Dutch: {{tt|nl|naar huis}}\n* Estonian: {{tt|et|koju}}\n* Faroese: {{tt|fo|heim}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kotiin}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|à la maison}}\n* Friulian: {{t-needed|fur}}\n* Galician: {{tt|gl|a casa}}\n* Georgian: {{t-needed|ka}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|nach Hause}}, {{tt+|de|nachhause}}, {{tt+|de|heimwärts}}, {{tt+|de|heim}}\n*: Alemannic German: {{tt|gsw|häi}}\n* Greek: {{tt|el|[[προς]] [[το]] [[σπίτι]]}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{tt|grc|οἴκαδε}}, {{q|Epic}} {{tt|grc|δόμονδε}}\n* Gujarati: {{t|gu|ઘરે}}\n* Hausa: {{t-needed|ha}}\n* Hawaiian: {{tt|haw|i kauhale}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|הביתה|tr=habáyta}}\n* Hindi: {{t-needed|hi}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|haza}}\n* Hunsrik: {{tt|hrx|hemm}}, {{tt|hrx|hemmzus}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|heim}}\n* Ido: {{tt+|io|adheme}}\n* Igbo: {{t-needed|ig}}\n* Indonesian: {{t-needed|id}}\n* Interlingua: {{t-needed|ia}}\n* Irish: {{tt|ga|abhaile}}\n* Italian: {{tt|it|a casa}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|家|tr=うちへ, uchi e|alt=家へ}}, {{tt+|ja|家|tr=うちに, uchi ni|alt=家に}}\n* Javanese: {{t-needed|jv}}\n* Kannada: {{t-needed|kn}}\n* Khmer: {{tt|km|ទៅផ្ទះ|tr=tɨv pteah}}\n* Korean: {{tt|ko|[[집]][[-에]]}}, {{tt|ko|[[집]][[-으로]]}}\n* Latin: {{tt+|la|domum}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t|lt|namo}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|дома}}\n* Navajo: {{tt|nv|hooghangóó}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt+|no|hjem}}, {{tt+|no|heim}}, {{tt|no|hjemover}}, {{tt|no|heimover}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{tt|nn|heim}}, {{tt|nn|heimover}}\n* Pashto: {{t-needed|ps}}\n* Pennsylvania German: {{tt|pdc|heem}}\n* Persian: {{t-needed|fa}}\n* Plautdietsch: {{tt|pdt|nohus}}\n* Polish: {{tt|pl|[[do]] [[dom]]u}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt|pt|para casa}}\n* Punjabi: {{tt|pnb|گھردو|tr=ghardo}} {{qualifier|Shahmukhi}}, {{tt|pa|ਘਰਦੋ|tr=ghardo}} {{qualifier|Gurmukhi}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|acasă}}\n* Romansh: {{tt|rm|a chasa}} {{qualifier|Rumantsch Grischun|Vallader}}, {{tt|rm|a casa}} {{qualifier|Sursilvan}}, {{tt|rm|a tgea}}, {{tt|rm|a tgeasa}} {{qualifier|Sutsilvan}}, {{tt|rm|a tgesa}} {{qualifier|Surmiran}}, {{tt|rm|a chesa}} {{qualifier|Puter}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|домо́й}}\n* Rwanda-Rundi: {{t-needed|rw}}\n* Sami:\n*: Northern Sami: {{tt|se|ruoktot}}\n* Sanskrit: {{t-needed|sa}}\n* Sardinian: {{t-needed|sc}}\n* Scots: {{tt|sco|hame}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|dhachaigh}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|кући}}\n*: Latin: {{tt+|sh|kući}}\n* Sicilian: {{t-needed|scn}}\n* Sindhi: {{t-needed|sd}}\n* Sinhalese: {{tt|si|ගෙදර දෙසට}}\n* Slovak: {{tt+|sk|domov}}\n* Slovene: {{tt+|sl|domôv}}\n* Somali: {{t-needed|so}}\n* Spanish: {{tt|es|a casa}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|hem}}, {{tt+|sv|hemåt}}\n* Tamil: {{t|ta|[[வீடு|வீட்டிற்]][[-கு|கு]]}}, {{t|ta|[[வீடு|வீட்]][[-ஐ|டை]] [[நோக்கு|நோக்]][[-இ|கி]]}}\n* Telugu: {{tt|te|ఇంటి వైపు}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|eve}}, {{tt|tr|eve doğru}}\n* Turkmen: {{t-needed|tk}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt|uk|додо́му}}\n* Urdu: {{t-needed|ur}}\n* Uyghur: {{t-needed|ug}}\n* Uzbek: {{t-needed|uz}}\n* Walloon: {{t-needed|wa}}\n* Welsh: {{tt+|cy|adref}}, {{tt|cy|adre}}\n* Wolof: {{t-needed|wo}}\n* Xhosa: {{t-needed|xh}}\n* Yiddish: {{tt|yi|אַהײם}}\n* Yoruba: {{t|yo|sílé}}\n* Zulu: {{t-needed|zu}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n}}<!-- close {{multitrans}} -->\n\n===References===\n* {{R:OneLook}}\n* {{R:Keywords 21st}}\n* {{R:Century 1911}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{pedia}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=ehmo|Mohe|hemo-}}\n\n{{cln|en|movement adverbs|position adverbs}}\n\n==Asturian==\n{{wp|ast:}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|ast|hombre||Llanes, Cabrales}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|ast|la|homō|homō, hominem}}, from {{inh|ast|itc-pro|*hemō}}, from {{inh|ast|ine-pro|*ǵʰmṓ|*ǵʰm̥mṓ}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{ast-pr}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{ast-noun|m}}\n\n# [[man]]\n#: {{uxi|ast|L''''home''' equí ye'l fíu María.|This '''man''' here is María's son.}}\n# [[person]]\n# [[husband]]\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{s|person}} {{l|ast|persona}}\n* {{s|husband}} {{l|ast|esposu}}, {{l|ast|maríu}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|ast|home del sacu}}\n* {{l|ast|ho}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:ast:DGLA}}\n* {{R:ast:DALLA}}\n\n{{C|ast|People}}\n\n==Catalan==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{dercat|ca|itc-ola|itc-pro|ine-pro|inh=3}}\n{{inh+|ca|roa-oca|home}}~{{m|roa-oca|hom}}, from {{inh|ca|la|homō|hominem|human|pos=n}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ca-IPA|ò}}\n* {{audio|ca|LL-Q7026 (cat)-Millars-home.wav|a=Valencia}}\n* {{rhyme|ca|ɔme|s=2}}\n* {{hyph|ca|ho|me}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{ca-noun|m|+,hòmens}}\n\n# [[man]]\n# [[husband]]\n#: {{syn|ca|cònjuge|espòs|marit}}\n\n====Antonyms====\n{{col|ca|title=woman\n|dona\n}}\n{{col|ca|title=wife\n|cònjuge\n|costella<ll:figuratively>\n|dona\n|esposa\n|muller\n}}\n\n====Hypernyms====\n{{col|ca|title=spouse\n|cònjuge\n}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col3|ca|home llop|homenada|homenejar|homenenc|homenera|homenet|homenia|homenívol|homenot}}\n\n====Related terms====\n{{col3|ca|homenatge|homenatjar|prohom}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|ca|interjection}}\n\n# {{n-g|A term of address for a man conveying [[annoyance]], [[impatience]], [[surprise]], [[disagreement]], etc.}}\n#: {{uxi|ca|'''Home''', no sigues bèstia!|'''Dude''', don't be stupid!}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:ca:IEC2}}\n* {{R:ca:GDLC}}\n* {{R:ca:DNV}}\n* {{R:ca:DCVB}}\n\n{{C|ca|Marriage|People}}\n\n==Classical Nahuatl==\n\n===Numeral===\n{{head|head=ho̊me|nci|numeral}}\n\n# {{lb|nci|[[w:Codex Magliabechiano|Codex Magliabechiano]]}} {{obsolete spelling of|nci|ōme}}\n\n==Esperanto==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{m|eo|homo}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{eo-pr}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{eo-head}}\n\n# [[humanly]]; in a human fashion\n\n==Finnish==\n{{wp|fi:}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|fi|urj-fin-pro|*homëh}} (compare {{cog|krl|homeh}}, {{cog|vot|õmõ}}), probably borrowed from {{der|fi|gem-pro|*swammaz}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{fi-pronunciation|*}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{fi-noun}}\n\n# [[mold]], [[mildew]] {{gloss|furry or woolly growth of tiny fungi}}\n#: {{ux|fi|Tämä leipä on '''homeessa'''.|This bread is '''moldy'''|lit=This bread is '''in mold'''.}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{fi-decl-hame|hom|||a}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|fi\n|homehtua\n|homeinen\n|homettaa\n}}\n\n{{col|fi|title=compounds\n|harmaahome\n|homeallergia\n|homealtistus\n|homeenvihreä\n|homeitiö\n|homejuusto\n|homekoira\n|homekorva\n|homekoulu\n|homemyrkky\n|homeongelma\n|homepilkku\n|homepöly\n|homepölykeuhko\n|homerihmasto\n|homesaneeraus\n|homesieni\n|homesiivous\n|homesuojattu\n|hometahra\n|hometalo\n|homevaurio\n|jalohome\n|kuparihome\n|lehtihome\n|lumihome\n|maitohome\n|pronssihome\n|punahome\n|punahomejuusto\n|sinihomejuusto\n|vesihome\n}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fi:KTSK|accessdate=2023-07-02}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|fi|a=ehmo|hemo}}\n\n{{C|fi|Botany}}\n\n==Galician==\n[[File:Da Vinci Vitruve Luc Viatour.jpg|thumb|''Home'' (\"man\")]]\n[[File:Carallán (4868362418).jpg|thumb|''Home'' (\"man\")]]\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|gl|homem||reinteg}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|gl|roa-opt|ome}}, {{m|roa-opt|omẽe}}, from {{inh|gl|la|homō|homō, hominem}}, from {{inh|gl|itc-pro|*hemō}}, from {{inh|gl|ine-pro|*ǵʰmṓ|*ǵʰm̥mṓ}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{gl-pr|hòme<audio:gl-home.ogg>}}\n* {{hyph|gl|ho|me}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{gl-noun|m}}\n\n# [[human]]; [[person]]\n#: {{ux|gl|q=proverb|Unha sebe tres anos dura; un can tres sebes; unha mula tres cans; un '''home''' tres mulas|A hedge lasts three years; a dog three hedges; a mule three dogs; a '''person''' three mules}}\n# [[mankind]]\n#: {{uxi|gl|O '''home''' chegou á Lúa en 1969|'''Mankind''' arrived to the Moon in 1969}}\n# [[man]] {{gl|adult male}}\n#: {{uxi|gl|q=proverb|'''Home''' casado muller é|The Married '''man''' is a woman}}\n# [[male]] human\n#: {{uxi|gl|q=proverb|'''Home''' pequeno fol de veleno|Small '''man''', skin [bag] of venom}}\n# [[husband]]\n#: {{uxi|gl|Éste é o meu '''home''', Xaquín|This is my '''husband''', Joachim}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n* {{U:gl:false friend|lar|en=home}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|gl|homiño|t=little man}}\n* {{l|gl|lobishome|t=werewolf}}\n* {{l|gl|ricohome|t=magnate}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|gl|interjection}}\n\n# [[man]]! {{n-g|(expresses surprise, or mild annoyance)}}\n#: {{uxi|gl|-Es o campión do mundo? Contento? -'''Home'''!...|-You're the champion of the world? Are you happy? -'''Man'''!... [Of course I'm happy, what kind of question is this?]}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|gl|ho}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{l|gl|persoa}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:gl:DRAG}}\n* {{R:gl:DDLG}}\n* {{R:gl:TILG}}\n* {{R:TLPGP}}\n* {{R:gl:Estraviz}}\n\n{{C|gl|People}}\n\n==Ingrian==\n[[Image:Verschimmeltes Brot 2008-12-07.JPG|thumb|Home leivän pääl.]]\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|izh|urj-fin-pro|*homëh}}. Cognates include {{cog|fi|home}} and {{cog|vep|homeh}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{izh-p|H=homeh}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|izh|noun}}\n\n# [[mould]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{izh-decl/lähe|m|m}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4|izh\n|homehtua}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:izh:Nirvi:1971|page=67}}\n* {{R:izh:Laanest:1997|page=37}}\n\n{{C|izh|Fungi}}\n\n==Italian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|it|:bor|en:home}}\n{{bor+|it|en|home}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{it-pr|hóm,!hóum<r:Olivetti><r:DiPI:home video>}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{it-noun|f|#}}\n\n# {{lb|it|computing}} {{l|en|home}} {{gloss|initial position of various computing objects}}\n\n===References===\n<references />\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|it|a=ehmo|ohmè}}\n\n==Leonese==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|roa-leo|la|homō|homō, hominem}}, from {{inh|roa-leo|itc-pro|*hemō}}, from {{inh|roa-leo|ine-pro|*ǵʰmṓ|*ǵʰm̥mṓ}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|roa-leo|noun|g=m|plural|homes}}\n\n# [[man]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:roa-leo:DCLLC}}\n\n==Macanese==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|mzs|hóme|hómi}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|mzs|pt|home}}, denasalized variant of {{m|pt|homem}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|mzs|/ˈɔme/|/ˈɔmi/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|mzs|noun|plural|home-home}}\n\n# [[man]]\n#: {{uxi|mzs|'''home-home''' di hoze|t='''men''' nowadays}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|mzs|mulé}}\n\n===References===\n* https://www.macaneselibrary.org/pub/english/uipatua.htm\n\n{{C|mzs|Male people}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}}\n\n# {{alt form|enm|hom||home}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|enm|pronoun|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|whom|t=whom|id=whom}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|enm|pronoun|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|hem|t=them|id=them}}\n\n===Etymology 4===\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}}\n\n# {{alt form|enm|hamme||enclosure; meadow}}\n\n===Etymology 5===\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|hame||hame {{gl|part of a harness}}}}\n\n===Etymology 6===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|enm|verb|altform=1}}\n\n# {{alt form|enm|hummen||to hum}}\n\n==Mirandese==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|ast|huome||rare|chiefly as an interjection}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|mwl|la|homō|homō, hominem}}, from {{inh|mwl|itc-pro|*hemō}}, from {{inh|mwl|ine-pro|*ǵʰmṓ|*ǵʰm̥mṓ}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{mwl-noun|m}}\n\n# [[man]]\n# [[husband]]\n\n====Antonyms====\n* {{l|mwl|mulhier}}\n\n{{C|mwl|Family|Human}}\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n\n===Verb===\n{{nn-verb-1}}\n\n# {{alt form|nn|homma|homa}} {{nn-fcon|2012}}\n\n==Old French==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n: ''see {{l|fro|hom}} for alternative nominative singular forms''\n{{col|fro\n|homme\n|honme\n|hume\n|onme\n|ume\n}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|fro|la-vul||*(h)omne}}, {{inh|fro|la|hominem}}, accusative singular of {{m|la|homō}}. The nominative form {{m|fro|hom}}, {{m|fro|om}}, {{m|fro|on}}, {{m|fro|hon}} derives from the Latin nominative {{m|la|homō}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|fro|/ˈu.mə/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{fro-noun|m|homes|hom|home}}\n\n# [[man]] (male adult human being)\n# [[man]] (mankind; ''Homo sapiens'')\n#* {{quote-book|fro|year=c. 1120|author=Philippe de Taon|title=[http://bestiary.ca/etexts/wright1841/bestiary%20of%20philippe%20de%20thaon%20-%20wright.pdf Bestiaire]|passage=O '''HOM''' de sancte vie, entent que signefie|translation=O MAN of sacred life, listen to what this means|line=476}}\n# [[vassal]]; [[manservant]]\n\n====Coordinate terms====\n* {{l|fro|fame|gloss=woman}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desctree|frm|homme}}\n* {{desc|nrf|houme}} {{qualifier|France}}, {{l|nrf|haomme}} {{qualifier|Guernsey}}, {{l|nrf|houmme}} {{qualifier|Jersey}}\n* {{desc|pcd|onme}}\n* {{desc|wa|ome}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Godefroy|homme}}\n* {{R:Godefroy|homme|supplement=1}}\n* {{R:Anglo-Norman On-Line Hub}}\n* {{R:FEW|4|455|title=homo}} (contains a reference to the nominative singular forms ''hom'', ''huem'' and ''om'')\n\n{{C|fro|People}}\n\n==Old Galician-Portuguese==\n\n===Noun===\n{{roa-opt-noun|m}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|roa-opt|ome}}\n\n==Old Occitan==\n\n===Noun===\n{{pro-noun|m|3=hom}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|pro|ome}}\n\n==Portuguese==\n\n===Etymology===\nDenasalization of {{l|pt|homem}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{pt-IPA|hô*me}}\n* {{rhyme|pt|ɔmɨ|õmi|q1=Portugal|q2=Brazil|s=2}}\n* {{hyph|pt|ho|me}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{pt-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|pt|nonstandard}} {{alt form of|pt|homem}}"}}